Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Dataset columns¶

  • id
  • imdb_id
  • popularity - Index indicating popularity
  • budget
  • revenue
  • original_title
  • cast - multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters
  • homepage - page of the movie
  • director - multiple values separated by pipe (|)
  • tagline
  • keywords - multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters
  • overview
  • runtime
  • genres - multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters
  • production_companies - multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters
  • release_date
  • vote_count
  • vote_average
  • release_year
  • budget_adj - budget of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.
  • revenue_adj - revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  2. Which genres are associated with high revenue movies?
  3. What actors are associated with high revenues movies?
  4. What directors are associated with high revenues movies?
  5. What production companies has the highest revenue?
  6. What production company spend highest budget?
  7. Is higher budget movies associated with higher revenue?
  8. Is run time associated with revenue?
  9. Is there correlation between users vote average and revenue?
  10. Is there correlation between popularity and revenue?

def count_zeros(df):
    """
    Prints Zeros counts for every column in DataFrame
    
    Args:
        df: Pandas DataFrame
        
    Returns:    
        View Zeros counts in every column.
    
    """
    for column_name in df.columns:
        Zeros_count = df[df[column_name] == 0][column_name].count()
        print('Column "{}" has {} Zeros'.format(column_name, Zeros_count))

def correct_date(date, year, sep= '/'):
    """
    Corrects date formats for in string format mm/dd/yy
    
    Args:
        date: date string to be corrected
        year: year for correction
        sep: seperator in date format
        
    Returns:    
        corrected date in mm/dd/yyyy format.
    
    """
    date_list = date.split(sep)
    year_ind = int(date_list[-1])
    if year_ind+2000 > year:
        date_list[-1] = str(year_ind+1900)
        date = sep.join(date_list)
    else:
        date_list[-1] = str(year_ind+2000)
        date = sep.join(date_list)
    
    return date

def replace_zeros(df, columns):
    """
    Replaces zeros with column's median in one or multiple columns, The column's median is calculated for non Zero values
    to avoid deviation from actual distribution.
    
    Args:
        df: Pandas DataFrame to work on
        columns: columns to replace its Zeros
        
    Returns:    
        Replaced dataframe as desired.
    
    """
    for column in columns:
        median_value = df[df[column] != 0].median()[column]
        df[column].replace(0, median_value, inplace= True)
        
def into_list(df, columns , sep):
    """
    Changes columns with list like values ,string seperated by a seperator, into python lists
    
    Args:
        df: Pandas DataFrame to work on
        columns: columns to turn its values into list
        sep: String seperator
        
    Returns:    
        Changed dataframe values into list.
    
    """
    for column in columns:
        df[column]= df[column].apply(lambda x: x.split(sep))

Dataset observed issues:¶

  1. NaN values in cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, genres and production_companies columns
  2. Duplicate rows
  3. Duplicate in original_title column
  4. Wrong data types in release_date
  5. Zeros , probably unknown values, in runtime, budget, revenue, budget_adj and revenue_adj columns
  6. Columns that has list like values seperated with pipe (|) charachter

In the previous steps we choose to fill Zeros in 'runtime','budget_adj' and 'revenue_adj' columns with their median for the following reasons:

  • Zeros are unknown values as no movie has zero runtime, budget or revenue_adj.
  • Rows with zero columns has other needed values in the rest of the columns.
  • Count of rows with Zero columns are more than 45% of total rows count so deleting them would affect accuracy of analysis
  • We used median for filling Zeros as it's less sensitive to outliers and won't affect whole dataset distribution and mean significantly

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

1. Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

We're determining most popular genre by using the count of produced movies in each genre across the years. We can't use popularity column as it represents current visits and votes not the actual popularity the year movie is produced.
First we need to create df_genres as a copy of df_cleaned then we use pandas.DataFrame.explode method to transform each genre of the list to a row

In [29]:
df_genres = df_cleaned.copy()
In [30]:
df_genres = df_genres.explode('genres')

Conclusions¶

Mutliple findings from analysis of asked questions have led to the following conslusions:

  • Most popular movie genre is Drama followed by Comedy based on number of movies produced in each genre for the dataset time frame from 1960 till 2015. Additional information about numbers of sold tickets for each movies will be useful
  • Adventure is the genre with the highest average revenue followed by Fantasy then Animation. Additional information about age ratings for each movies will be useful
  • Daisy Ridley has the highest average revenue between actors followed by Robert MacNaughton.
  • Hamilton Luske and Clyde Geronimi have the highest average revenue between directors followed by George Lucas.
    Hamilton Luske and Clyde Geronimi worked together in the same movies and have the same average revenue.
  • Hoya Productions has the highest average revenue of all production companies followed by Truenorth Productions.
  • Boram Entertainment Inc. has the highest average budget of all production companies followed by Second Mate Productions
  • There is a moderate linear positive correlation between spent Budget and Revenue. Further statistical tests are needed to confirm correlation and its cause.
  • There is a Moderate linear positive correlation between Popularity and Revenue. Further statistical tests are needed to confirm correlation and its cause.
  • There is a weak linear positive correlation between Runtime and Revenue but it may be neglected as it's insignificant. This is also the case for the correlation between vote average and Revenue.

Dataset and Analysis have limitations:

  • Dataset has many unknown and missing values as shown in Data Wrangling step
  • Correlations found don't imply causation and futher testing and analysis is needed
  • More information about age ratings, for how long movie was in theaters and number of sold tickets for example will be useful
